218
00:25:43,192 --> 00:25:48,376
In its most basic components, an action game is made up of collision, movement, and object states.

219
00:25:52,158 --> 00:25:55,960
Taken together, collision and movement make up what we call physics in games.

220
00:26:10,048 --> 00:26:14,949
But of course, when it comes to game development, you don't want the sort of physics you find in a textbook,

221
00:26:15,509 --> 00:26:18,250
but a kind that fits the needs of the game you're making.

222
00:26:19,450 --> 00:26:22,351
We call this game physics.

223
00:26:22,371 --> 00:26:26,112
This game physics has been born from various games since the NES era.

224
00:26:26,812 --> 00:26:28,633
And this is what we call game physics.

225
00:26:29,193 --> 00:26:35,035
Since the NES era, a plethora of games have added to our understanding of this concept of game physics.

226
00:26:44,871 --> 00:27:01,876
Game physics is, in other words, a lie.

227
00:27:01,896 --> 00:27:02,397
Why do we lie?

228
00:27:06,737 --> 00:27:10,660
