00:27:11,641 --> 00:27:13,842
But why would you need to tell lies?

230
00:27:19,966 --> 00:27:23,509
This is something we do to increase controllability and responsiveness.

231
00:27:23,929 --> 00:27:26,271
In other words, to fulfill the demands of game design.

232
00:27:26,291 --> 00:27:30,614
Sometimes to make it easier to process and to optimize.

233
00:27:33,518 --> 00:27:39,601
We also end up telling these lies to optimize processing power and sometimes even to increase the sense of realism.

234
00:27:41,262 --> 00:27:47,106
On the other hand, if we're telling lies, what use do we have for the laws of physics?

235
00:28:03,991 --> 00:28:06,152
I think it's so that we can build a sense of trust

236
00:28:06,232 --> 00:28:07,613
between the player and the game.

237
00:28:08,254 --> 00:28:10,115
Players encounter in-game events

238
00:28:10,195 --> 00:28:11,556
they've observed in the real world

239
00:28:11,776 --> 00:28:14,738
and come to believe in the game's particular set of rules.

240
00:28:15,859 --> 00:28:18,300
And that's the basis for the clever lies we tell in games.

241
00:28:32,378 --> 00:28:35,019
And of course, the Zelda series is no exception to this.

242
00:28:35,780 --> 00:28:38,601
Past titles have made ample use of game physics

243
00:28:38,781 --> 00:28:41,122
to make performing actions and solving puzzles

244
00:28:41,203 --> 00:28:41,983
more intuitive.

245
00:28:44,985 --> 00:28:46,125
How to tell a clever lie,

246
00:28:46,145 --> 00:28:49,047
or how to express a phenomenon unique to the virtual world,

247
00:28:49,067 --> 00:28:50,688
is one of the fun things about programming.

248
00:28:53,117 --> 00:28:58,422
