00:34:46,438 --> 00:34:48,019
but illusory kind of floating.

309
00:34:55,321 --> 00:34:56,982
Now, I'd like to get back to the theme

310
00:34:57,082 --> 00:35:00,163
of multiplicative gameplay that Mr. Fujibayashi mentioned.

311
00:35:01,043 --> 00:35:02,743
As we tried to think of a game physics,

312
00:35:02,803 --> 00:35:03,424
we realized one thing.

313
00:35:03,444 --> 00:35:05,944
If we connect the world with consistent physics,

314
00:35:05,964 --> 00:35:07,505
we'll want to try more and more things.

315
00:35:11,860 --> 00:35:16,363
In our various experiments of trial and error with game physics, there was one thing that we noticed.

316
00:35:17,004 --> 00:35:20,707
If you unify your game world with a set of consistent physics rules,

317
00:35:21,027 --> 00:35:24,449
the player will come up with ideas for all sorts of things they want to try.

318
00:35:24,469 --> 00:35:29,433
So for example, this metal slab is placed here to allow you to cross this river.

319
00:35:40,398 --> 00:35:45,441
But once you pick it up, you might find yourself suddenly wanting to try dropping it on top of an enemy.

320
00:35:51,603 --> 00:35:55,465
Once you see that log floating on the river, it's natural to want to try jumping on it.

321
00:35:56,245 --> 00:36:00,167
Just riding a log down a river seems like it would be fun. You might remember this from the prototype earlier.

322
00:36:16,585 --> 00:36:22,767
動くものにも登れるということは、巨大な敵の体に登れたらどういう戦いが作れるか。 And if you can climb moving objects, what sort of battle would unfold if you were fighting a giant enemy that you could climb? ステーシスで勢いをつけたオブジェクトに登ると、さて何が起きるか。

