00:36:59,722 --> 00:37:04,445
This would be a world where combining simple elements could produce complex results, where

331
00:37:04,505 --> 00:37:08,046
you'd feel the thrill of imagining the things you wanted to try as you played.

332
00:37:08,066 --> 00:37:09,587
I realized that was the game we should try to make.

333
00:37:35,180 --> 00:37:36,581
Now, I'd like to switch topics a bit.

334
00:37:37,141 --> 00:37:39,163
These two are members of our development team.

335
00:37:46,948 --> 00:37:50,571
They're discussing just how we should go about breaking these conventions of ours.

336
00:37:51,331 --> 00:37:52,512
Looks like they're having a good time.

337
00:37:58,259 --> 00:37:59,820
This must be a heartfelt conversation.

338
00:38:05,004 --> 00:38:09,347
Okay now it looks like things are really heating up.

339
00:38:10,027 --> 00:38:12,709
It was during this discussion that a certain key word was born.

340
00:38:12,729 --> 00:38:18,112
If physics engines are such a thing, why don't you ever hear about chemistry engines?

341
00:38:32,596 --> 00:38:37,118
As you likely know, the Zelda series has long made use of the sort of events that occur

342
00:38:37,178 --> 00:38:39,078
in chemistry as in-game elements.

343
00:38:39,999 --> 00:38:43,340
Just like with physics, creating puzzles with solutions that reference the way the real

344
00:38:43,360 --> 00:38:45,721
world works can help players solve them instinctively.

345
00:38:59,905 --> 00:39:02,027
We decided to develop a chemistry engine.

346
00:39:06,349 --> 00:39:08,190
So what exactly is this chemistry engine?

347
00:39:08,210 --> 00:39:12,693
In other words, it is a computer that calculates motion based on rules.

348
00:39:13,691 --> 00:39:18,054
One way of describing a physics engine is as a rule-based movement calculator.

349
00:39:24,719 --> 00:39:29,903
In comparison, we decided the chemistry engine would be a rule-based state calculator.

350
00:39:31,744 --> 00:39:35,787
I mentioned this before, but action games are made up of collision plus movement plus changing states.

351
00:39:47,486 --> 00:39:51,427
And it's our chemistry engine that calculates these changes in the state of things.

352
00:39:53,968 --> 00:39:57,849
So I'd like to give a simple explanation of our design to show just what sort of calculations

353
00:39:58,189 --> 00:39:59,329
are being run by this chemistry engine.

354
00:40:08,691 --> 00:40:12,212
First, we refer to things like fire, water, and ice that don't hold a constant solid form as elements.

355
00:40:12,272 --> 00:40:14,772
Next, we refer to objects such as players, weapons, and other objects as materials.

356
00:40:30,095 --> 00:40:33,156
Next, we call solid objects like trees and rocks,

357
00:40:33,717 --> 00:40:37,138
even the player character and weapons, materials.

358
00:40:42,261 --> 00:40:47,003
The chemistry engine uses these things to make its calculations based on three simple rules.

359
00:40:48,784 --> 00:40:49,624
First up is rule one.

360
00:40:49,904 --> 00:40:51,805
Elements can change the state of materials.

361
00:41:00,263 --> 00:41:02,184
So the leaves on the tree burn up and disappear.

362
00:41:04,205 --> 00:41:04,726
Next is rule two.

363
00:41:04,746 --> 00:41:06,427
Elements are able to change each other's states.

364
00:41:06,447 --> 00:41:08,568
So the fire disappeared when it came in contact

365
00:41:08,588 --> 00:41:09,028
with the water.

366
00:41:25,403 --> 00:41:30,826
And finally, rule three, materials cannot influence each other's states.

367
00:41:35,269 --> 00:41:36,910
So you can see neither of them changed.

368
00:41:39,112 --> 00:41:41,513
And that's the chemistry engine in a nutshell.

369
00:41:41,573 --> 00:41:43,915
The model is an extremely simple one, but allows for the expression of all sorts of

370
00:41:43,935 --> 00:41:44,135
events.

371
00:42:04,045 --> 00:42:15,954
Whoa!

372
00:42:16,014 --> 00:42:16,674
What's that?

373
00:42:26,244 --> 00:42:28,926
All these types of interactions in the game are realized by the chemistry engine.

374
00:42:28,986 --> 00:42:31,128
Wait, are electricity and wind a part of chemistry?

375
00:42:58,175 --> 00:43:02,158
In a textbook, the answer is of course no, but in the chemistry engine, you bet they

376
00:43:02,238 --> 00:43:02,338
are.

377
00:43:02,358 --> 00:43:06,482
Aside from rigid body dynamics, we consider all phenomena that occur in nature to be chemistry.

378
00:43:22,821 --> 00:43:25,963
And so for our purposes, things like wind and electricity

379
00:43:26,043 --> 00:43:27,884
are all considered to be elements.

380
00:43:28,544 --> 00:43:31,426
Again, treating them this way gives us a simplified method

381
00:43:31,466 --> 00:43:32,827
with which to model the world.

