00:43:45,854 --> 00:43:49,536
Instead, we wanted to create a state calculator for all these

389
00:43:49,636 --> 00:43:51,457
objects that are connected to one another.

390
00:43:54,158 --> 00:43:56,239
There's one other reason we referred to this sort of thing as chemistry.

391
00:43:56,259 --> 00:44:01,301
During development, we called this multiplicative gameplay we were trying to create chemical

392
00:44:01,501 --> 00:44:01,861
reaction play.

393
00:44:20,598 --> 00:44:26,801
This engine is the device that makes this sort of play possible, so in that way too, it can be considered chemistry.

394
00:44:28,823 --> 00:44:31,704
Elements can generate energy and impact the physical world.

395
00:44:31,724 --> 00:44:36,427
This is how the world is connected to the rules of physics and chemistry.

396
00:44:37,307 --> 00:44:42,130
Given the right situation, elements can also generate energy and impact the physical world.

397
00:44:42,671 --> 00:44:48,694
In this way, all the constituent parts of the world we created are governed by our rules of physics and chemistry.

398
00:45:28,928 --> 00:45:31,870
And with that, we had the game that we had hoped to make, one that used multiplication

399
00:45:31,890 --> 00:45:33,051
to increase the things you were able to do.

400
00:45:52,306 --> 00:45:54,888
Earlier, Mr. Fujibayashi posed the question,

401
00:45:55,468 --> 00:45:57,910
how can we create a game that uses multiplication

402
00:45:57,970 --> 00:45:59,231
to expand gameplay?

403
00:45:59,971 --> 00:46:01,632
It turns out our answer to this was

404
00:46:01,672 --> 00:46:03,914
to build connections between everything in the world.

405
00:46:03,934 --> 00:46:08,997
SPEAKER 2 IN JAPANESE

406
00:46:10,518 --> 00:46:12,159
This means that everything you see in the game

407
00:46:12,279 --> 00:46:14,121
is linked together, so to speak.

408
00:46:15,482 --> 00:46:16,522
SPEAKER 1 IN JAPANESE

409
00:46:22,368 --> 00:46:24,809
And these connections don't simply occur by accident.

410
00:46:25,349 --> 00:46:27,330
Instead, they're intentionally designed

411
00:46:27,450 --> 00:46:30,531
to have an overall consistency and to feel instinctive.

412
00:46:34,132 --> 00:46:36,913
And of course, they contain all sorts of those clever lies

413
00:46:36,953 --> 00:46:37,554
we like to tell.

414
00:46:37,574 --> 00:46:41,575
We didn't have a firm belief in this approach from the start.

415
00:46:41,595 --> 00:46:44,256
So we took the 2D approach to make the prototyping process as fast as possible.

416
00:46:44,356 --> 00:46:45,397
And that's what we call 2D Zelda.

417
00:46:51,120 --> 00:46:53,561
But when we started out, we had no guarantee

418
00:46:53,621 --> 00:46:55,323
that this sort of approach would work.

419
00:46:55,963 --> 00:46:59,205
So I used 2D graphics to quickly create a prototype

420
00:46:59,426 --> 00:47:00,506
as a proof of concept.

